I"Õ<p>If you want to operate on 9600 1 pixel by 1 pixel files at a time to form HD-width frames (i.e. 1920px wide) with GraphicsMagick (1920 pixels per row *5rows = 9600), hereâ€™s a <a href="https://github.com/rtanglao/rtgram/blob/gh-pages/IG-VANCOUVER_2014/RENUMBERED/TOP10/TOPCOLOUR/make1920By5PixelPNG.sh">bash script</a>:</p>

<div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>#!/bin/bash
files=(*.jpg )
frame=0
for ((i=0; i&lt;${#files[*]}; i+=9600)); do
  let â€œframe++â€
  gm montage -verbose -tile 1920x5 +frame +shadow +label \
  -geometry 1x1+0+0 â€œ${files[@]:i:9600}â€\
  `printf â€œframe-%5.5u.pngâ€ â€œ$frameâ€`
done
</code></pre></div></div>

<ol>
  <li>Why not just do this with ruby? Because bash is lighter weight</li>
  <li>Why do so few and split up into â€œframesâ€? Because graphicsmagick takes up lots of memory and runs slowly when you try to do all files in 1 big command line invocation.</li>
</ol>
